        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal vent; anoxic; H2-rich; pH 9-11\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 with H2 to surface-bound formyl/formate species that desorb as formate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"CO2 reduction to formate on Fe-S minerals is central to vent geochemistry and consistent with iron-sulfur world models used to supply reduced C1 units to later protometabolism; this step is supported by hydrothermal Fe-S catalysis studies and the vent framework summarized in the report (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Russell & Martin, 2004).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal C1-C2 carbon fixation to acetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite\", \"magnetite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent pH gradient; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential reduction and C-C bond formation on Fe-S/oxide surfaces generate acetate from reduced C1 carbon and CO2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Acetate production from reduced carbon species under hydrothermal Fe-S catalysis is a standard prebiotic carbon-fixation analog to acetyl-CoA chemistry and provides a bridge from geochemistry to alpha-keto acid formation (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal synthesis of glyoxylate from reduced carbon feedstock\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite\", \"pyrite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-470K\",