, "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline hydrothermal vent; anoxic; H2-rich; pH 9-11"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 with H2 to surface-bound formyl/formate species that desorb as formate.", "reasoning": "CO2 reduction to formate on Fe-S minerals is central to vent geochemistry and consistent with iron-sulfur world models used to supply reduced C1 units to later protometabolism; this step is supported by hydrothermal Fe-S catalysis studies and the vent framework summarized in the report (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Russell & Martin, 2004)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal C1-C2 carbon fixation to acetate", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite", "magnetite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent pH gradient; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Sequential reduction and C-C bond formation on Fe-S/oxide surfaces generate acetate from reduced C1 carbon and CO2.", "reasoning": "Acetate production from reduced carbon species under hydrothermal Fe-S catalysis is a standard prebiotic carbon-fixation analog to acetyl-CoA chemistry and provides a bridge from geochemistry to alpha-keto acid formation (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal synthesis of glyoxylate from reduced carbon feedstock", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite", "pyrite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-470K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor hydrothermal; anoxic redox gradients"}, "mechanism": "Partial oxidation-state adjustment and C-C bond formation among reduced carbon intermediates furnish glyoxylate as an alpha-keto acid precursor.", "reasoning": "Glyoxylate is a key node in abiotic keto-acid networks and is required by the Stubbs-Moran pyruvate/glyoxylate protometabolic chemistry leading toward alpha-ketoglutarate; inclusion here is a necessary connection from vent carbon fixation to that experimentally demonstrated network (Stubbs et al., 2020; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Hydrothermal synthesis of pyruvate from CO2 and H2", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite", "greigite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Multielectron reduction and carbon assembly on mineral surfaces generate the three-carbon alpha-keto acid pyruvate.", "reasoning": "The user-specified hydrothermal framework includes pyruvate synthesis on magnetite/greigite and pyruvate is explicitly identified in the research report as a critical precursor feeding abiotic r-TCA-like chemistry toward alpha-ketoglutarate and then proline (Muchowska et al., 2019; Stubbs & Moran, 2022)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Surface atmospheric-volcanic generation of hydrogen cyanide", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "molybdenite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 photocatalytic mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "false", "other": "UV-irradiated volcanic plume/steam atmosphere; lightning energy input; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "High-energy atmospheric chemistry and photochemical fixation generate cyanide that is trapped in surface waters and mineral-rich basins.", "reasoning": "The report identifies HCN as the primary carbon/nitrogen source in proline synthesis and cites atmospheric lightning and volcanic settings as the source of cyanide inventories, with volcanic Miller-type experiments later yielding proline-bearing mixtures upon reanalysis (Johnson et al., 2