mal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-amino-4-oxopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamate-5-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-oxopyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C)\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-proline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)/t4-/m0/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H10N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carboxamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"prolinamide\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Cu-photoredox coupling of HCN and acetylene to acrylonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"308K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox with UV; mineral-assisted surface setting\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-irradiated cyanosulfidic pool; neutral to mildly alkaline conditions; acetylene supplied volcanically\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox chemistry mediates C-C bond formation between HCN-derived carbon/nitrogen and acetylene to give the C3 nitrile acrylonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the key chain-extension entry into the Sutherland-style proline network, specifically identified in the literature report as the critical step assembling the five-carbon proline skeleton via acrylonitrile. Surface UV and cyanosulfidic conditions are required; mineral agents here represent the required surface mineral context while Cu photoredox is the primary documented catalyst. Supported by the cyanosulfidic systems chemistry framework summarized from Xu et al., 2020 and related Sutherland-group work; environmental framing also consistent with Patel et al., 2015. This step is literature-grounded, unlike the previously rejected implausible invention of HCN or acetylene from missing feedstocks.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive homologation of acrylonitrile to 2-aminopentanedinitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"308K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV photoredox cyanosulfidic chemistry\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Neutral pH, H2S as stoichiometric reductant, repeated irradiation/reduction sequence\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acrylonitrile undergoes cyanation/reductive homologation under cyanosulfidic UV conditions, with H2S serving as reductant, yielding the amino dinitrile precursor.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research report explicitly identifies reductive homologation of acrylonitrile in the presence of H2S as producing 2-aminopentanedinitrile. This is central and should not be replaced by speculative alternatives. Supported by the cyanosulfidic amino acid synthesis logic of Sutherland-group chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyclization of 2-aminopentanedinitrile to pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite, ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Mineral concentration and templating\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Evaporative concentration favors intramolecular ring closure in shallow pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The amino dinitrile undergoes intramolecular nucleophilic attack and ring closure to a five-membered pyrrolidine nitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies cyclization of the five-carbon dinitrile to pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile as the immediate pre-proline step. Ring closure is acknowledged as a bottleneck in dilute solution, so mineral concentration in evaporative settings is used here to address the literature-noted challenge without changing the known intermediate. The exact mineral catalyst is less directly documented, so this mineral-assistance framing is partly connective but consistent with the report's emphasis on mineral surfaces overcoming entropic barriers; supported by Xu et al., 2020 and the general mineral concentration role discussed in the review.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile to proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"353-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"None required; hydrothermal or evaporitic maturation\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Elevated temperature; hydrolysis is kinetically slow and condition-sensitive\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrile hydration and subsequent hydrolysis convert the cyclic aminonitrile into the carboxylic acid proline.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly identifies hydrolysis of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile as the final step in both the cyanosulfidic and Strecker-like routes, and notes that nitrile hydrolysis is a major kinetic bottleneck often requiring temperatures above 80 degrees C or mineral assistance. This reaction therefore remains central but rate-limiting. Supported by the review summary of Strecker and cyanosulfidic chemistry and general aminonitrile hydrolysis literature; see Strecker framework as discussed in Miller, 1957 tradition and modern review synthesis, plus the systems analysis in the provided report. The literature supports abiotic proline formation but not direct exclusive L-selectivity.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Intramolecular cyclization of 4-aminobutanal to 1-pyrroline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Mineral-assisted concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Neutral to mildly alkaline pH 7-9; evaporative concentration assists imine formation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"4-Aminobutanal undergoes spontaneous intramolecular condensation to the cyclic imine 1-pyrroline.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report specifically describes the Strecker-like proline mechanism as proceeding through 4-aminobutanal and 1-pyrroline. This ring closure is chemically plausible under the stated pH range but entropically challenging in dilute solution, so concentration on mineral-rich surfaces is used to make the known route geochemically coherent. Supported by the Strecker-like pathway summarized in the report; this step is literature-supported though upstream production of 4-aminobutanal remains an open systems question.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN addition to 1-pyrroline yielding pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Mineral-assisted cyanation\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Neutral to mildly alkaline pH 7-9 in aqueous solution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanide addition to the cyclic imine forms the corresponding cyclic alpha-aminonitrile, pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the key Strecker-like cyanation step explicitly described in the literature summary: 1-pyrroline plus HCN gives pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile. Supported by classical Strecker logic and the specific proline-focused pathway discussed in the report. The cyclic aminonitrile produced converges with the cyanosulfidic route, matching the requested network convergence.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal synthesis of pyruvate from CO2 and H2\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Magnetite/greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline vent conditions with redox gradients and Fe-S mineral surfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential CO2 reduction and C-C bond-forming protometabolic chemistry on Fe-S/oxide mineral surfaces generates the alpha-keto acid pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The user instructions specifically require pyruvate synthesis from CO2 and H2 on magnetite/greigite in hydrothermal environments, and the report places pyruvate as a key alpha-keto-acid precursor for the proto-metabolic route to proline. While individual elementary steps remain an active research area, the hydrothermal generation of pyruvate-like rTCA intermediates on Fe-bearing minerals is aligned with metabolism-first scenarios. Supported conceptually by Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2019; Stubbs et al., 2020-2022 as summarized in the report. This is a connective but literature-consistent node.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal synthesis of glyoxylate from CO2 under iron-sulfur catalysis\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS/FeS2 mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Anoxic subseafloor hydrothermal setting; redox and pH gradients\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 reduction and partial carbonyl retention on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces generate reactive C2 oxoacid inventory including glyoxylate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies glyoxylate as one of the crucial alpha-keto acid precursors feeding abiotic rTCA analog chemistry. Direct geochemical generation remains less well constrained than downstream coupling chemistry, so this step is somewhat connective, but it stays within the hydrothermal Fe-S framework emphasized in the report and does not introduce unsupported feedstocks. Supported broadly by iron-sulfur world chemistry and by the central role of glyoxylate in abiotic metabolic analog studies (Muchowska et al., 2019; Stubbs and Moran, 2020-2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Abiotic aldol-like coupling of pyruvate and glyoxylate to alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"353K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe-bearing mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Mild hydrothermal aqueous conditions approximating abiotic rTCA analog chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate and glyoxylate undergo abiotic carbon-carbon coupling within a non-enzymatic reductive TCA analog network to form alpha-ketoglutarate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is one of the strongest literature-supported hydrothermal/protometabolic links to proline. The report explicitly states that recent studies by Stubbs and Moran showed pyruvate plus glyoxylate can generate alpha-ketoglutarate under mild aqueous conditions in abiotic rTCA analog networks. Supported by Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2019 and Stubbs et al., 2020-2022.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"353K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe minerals in hydrothermal aqueous medium\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Mild vent-like conditions; ammonia as amine donor analogue\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The alpha-keto acid accepts nitrogen via abiotic transamination/reductive amination chemistry to give glutamate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report states that alpha-ketoglutarate reacts with an amine donor such as glycine or ammonia to form glutamate, and cites experimental transamination of alpha-ketoglutarate under mild aqueous conditions. The exact catalyst in the cited yield study is alum, but the present network embeds this within the required hydrothermal mineral context while preserving the documented transformation. Supported by Stubbs and Moran, 2020-2022; the report also notes a 44% glutamate yield at 80 degrees C in the presence of AlK(SO4)2, highlighting plausibility though catalyst identity varies.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Partial reduction of glutamate to glutamate-5-semialdehyde and spontaneous cyclization to P5C\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"313-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"variable\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+ or transition-metal-mediated reduction possible\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Concentrated prebiotic pool or mineral interface; spontaneous intramolecular cyclization after partial reduction\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glutamate undergoes partial reduction to the semialdehyde, which rapidly cyclizes intramolecularly to Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly gives this as the hydrothermal/biochemical logic congruent with modern biology: glutamate is partially reduced to glutamate-5-semialdehyde, which spontaneously cyclizes to P5C. The reduction is proposed to be driven by H2 or transition-metal ions such as Fe2+. Supported by the report's synthesis of modern biochemical analogy and hydrothermal plausibility; this remains a mechanistically plausible but less directly benchmarked abiotic step than pyruvate/glyoxylate coupling.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of P5C to proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"313-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"variable\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+ or other transition metal reductants\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Anoxic reducing conditions; hydrothermal or mineral-interface maturation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The cyclic imine/carboxylate P5C is reduced at the imine center to afford proline.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly identifies reduction of P5C by H2 or transition metal ions such as Fe2+ as the terminal step of the proto-metabolic route to proline. This route aligns with modern proline biosynthesis and is therefore highly relevant for continuity from geochemistry to biochemistry. Supported by Stubbs and Moran, 2020-2022 as contextual support for abiotic protometabolism, and by the biochemical analogy discussed in the provided review.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydration of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile to prolinamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"353K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Aqueous thermal maturation\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Evaporitic or geothermal maturation conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Partial hydrolysis of the nitrile converts it to the corresponding amide, prolinamide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report specifically identifies prolinamide as a stable prebiotic intermediate detected in simulated synthesis and a precursor to proline-containing cyclic dipeptides. Including it as a late branch captures literature-supported maturation chemistry and increases network connectivity. Supported by the review's discussion of prolinamide in wet-dry prebiotic chemistry; this step is plausible though often less emphasized than full hydrolysis to proline.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of prolinamide to proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"353-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Thermal aqueous hydrolysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Wet-dry or geothermal cycling can promote conversion\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Amide hydrolysis yields the free amino acid proline.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This maturation step follows from the report's identification of prolinamide as a prebiotic precursor and aligns with standard hydrolysis chemistry under geothermal or evaporitic conditions. Supported by the prolinamide discussion in the provided review and by general prebiotic amide hydrolysis logic. It also provides an alternative final approach to the target from the same nitrile hub.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical cyanosulfidic nitrile route\",\n      \"description\": \"UV-driven surface synthesis of proline from HCN and acetylene through acrylonitrile, amino dinitrile, and cyclic aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic route with amide maturation\",\n      \"description\": \"Same surface nitrile route, but the cyclic nitrile first hydrates to prolinamide before final hydrolysis to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker-like cyclic imine route\",\n      \"description\": \"4-Aminobutanal cyclizes to 1-pyrroline, cyanates to pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, then hydrolyzes to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_004\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker-like route with prolinamide branch\",\n      \"description\": \"The cyclic imine route converges at pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, then proceeds through prolinamide before hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal proto-metabolic route from CO2\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal carbon fixation generates pyruvate and glyoxylate, which couple to alpha-ketoglutarate and proceed through glutamate and P5C to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal route emphasizing pyruvate hub\",\n      \"description\": \"Focuses on pyruvate as a hydrothermal hub feeding alpha-ketoglutarate formation and then the glutamate-P5C sequence.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal route emphasizing glyoxylate hub\",\n      \"description\": \"Focuses on glyoxylate as the convergent C2 oxoacid feeding alpha-ketoglutarate and the downstream proto-biosynthetic logic.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate-centered maturation route\",\n      \"description\": \"Begins at the common hydrothermal hub alpha-ketoglutarate and converts it to proline through glutamate and P5C.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile convergence route\",\n      \"description\": \"Any upstream chemistry that reaches pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile can access proline directly by hydrolysis, making the cyclic aminonitrile a major convergence hub.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"P5C convergence route\",\n      \"description\": \"Any upstream proto-metabolic chemistry that reaches P5C can reduce it to proline, making P5C the biochemical convergence hub.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_017\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_017\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": []\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Proline", "overall_strategy": "The network follows the literature-supported view that prebiotic proline emerged from interconnected geochemical niches rather than a single linear route. Three experimentally and conceptually grounded route families are integrated: (1) surface cyanosulfidic chemistry in which HCN and acetylene undergo Cu-photoredox coupling to acrylonitrile, reductive homologation to 2-aminopentanedinitrile, cyclization to pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, and hydrolysis to proline; (2) a Strecker-like surface route in which 4-aminobutanal cyclizes to 1-pyrroline, then cyanates to the same pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile hub before hydrolysis; and (3) a hydrothermal proto-metabolic route in which CO2 reduction gives pyruvate and glyoxylate, their abiotic coupling forms alpha-ketoglutarate, then transamination/reduction/cyclization gives glutamate, glutamate-5-semialdehyde, P5C, and finally proline. Biochemical/prebiotic maturation adds prolinamide as a late branch and clay-assisted concentration as a systems-level connector. Because literature support is for abiotic synthesis of proline generally rather than direct asymmetric formation of pure L-proline, the target is designated L-proline as requested but the reasoning explicitly notes that the primary synthesis steps likely produce racemic proline followed by possible enrichment/selection.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "C2H2", "iupac_name": "ethyne", "common_name": "acetylene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2/c1-2/h1-2H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "sulfane", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": "null"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C3H3N", "iupac_name": "prop-2-enenitrile", "common_name": "acrylonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H3N/c1-2-3-4/h2H,1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C5H7N3", "iupac_name": "2-aminopentane-1,5-dinitrile", "common_name": "2-aminopentanedinitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C5H8N2", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "common_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C4H9NO", "iupac_name": "4-aminobutanal", "common_name": "4-aminobutyraldehyde", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C4H7N", "iupac_name": "3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole", "common_name": "1-pyrroline", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H3O3-", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoate", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)/p-1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C2H2O3", "iupac_