 "UV-irradiated cyanosulfidic pool; neutral to mildly alkaline conditions; acetylene supplied volcanically"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox chemistry mediates C-C bond formation between HCN-derived carbon/nitrogen and acetylene to give the C3 nitrile acrylonitrile.", "reasoning": "This is the key chain-extension entry into the Sutherland-style proline network, specifically identified in the literature report as the critical step assembling the five-carbon proline skeleton via acrylonitrile. Surface UV and cyanosulfidic conditions are required; mineral agents here represent the required surface mineral context while Cu photoredox is the primary documented catalyst. Supported by the cyanosulfidic systems chemistry framework summarized from Xu et al., 2020 and related Sutherland-group work; environmental framing also consistent with Patel et al., 2015. This step is literature-grounded, unlike the previously rejected implausible invention of HCN or acetylene from missing feedstocks."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Reductive homologation of acrylonitrile to 2-aminopentanedinitrile", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_001", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photoredox cyanosulfidic chemistry", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Neutral pH, H2S as stoichiometric reductant, repeated irradiation/reduction sequence"}, "mechanism": "Acrylonitrile undergoes cyanation/reductive homologation under cyanosulfidic UV conditions, with H2S serving as reductant, yielding the amino dinitrile precursor.", "reasoning": "The deep research report explicitly identifies reductive homologation of acrylonitrile in the presence of H2S as producing 2-aminopentanedinitrile. This is central and should not be replaced by speculative alternatives. Supported by the cyanosulfidic amino acid synthesis logic of Sutherland-group chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Cyclization of 2-aminopentanedinitrile to pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borate minerals (colemanite, ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Mineral concentration and templating", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Evaporative concentration favors intramolecular ring closure in shallow pools"}, "mechanism": "The amino dinitrile undergoes intramolecular nucleophilic attack and ring closure to a five-membered pyrrolidine nitrile.", "reasoning": "The report identifies cyclization of the five-carbon dinitrile to pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile as the immediate pre-proline step. Ring closure is acknowledged as a bottleneck in dilute solution, so mineral concentration in evaporative settings is used here to address the literature-noted challenge without changing the known intermediate. The exact mineral catalyst is less directly documented, so this mineral-assistance framing is partly connective but consistent with the report's emphasis on mineral surfaces overcoming entropic barriers; supported by Xu et al., 2020 and the general mineral concentration role discussed in the review."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Hydrolysis of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile to proline", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "353-373K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "None required; hydrothermal or evaporitic maturation", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Elevated temperature; hydrolysis is kinetically slow and condition-sensitive"}, "mechanism": "Nitrile hydration and subsequent hydrolysis convert the cyclic aminonitrile into the carboxylic acid proline.", "reasoning": "The report explicitly identifies hydrolysis of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile as the final step in both the cyanosulfidic and Strecker-like routes, and notes that nitrile hydrolysis is a major kinetic bottleneck often requiring temperatures above 80 degrees C or mineral assistance. This reaction therefore remains central but rate-limiting. Supported by the review summary of Strecker and cyanosulfidic chemistry and general aminonitrile hydrolysis literature; see Strecker framework as discussed in Miller, 1957 tradition and modern review synthesis, plus the systems analysis in the provided report. The literature supports abiotic proline formation but not direct exclusive L-selectivity."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Intramolecular cyclization of 4-aminobutanal to 1-pyrroline", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Mineral-assisted concentration", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Neutral to mildly alkaline pH 7-9; evaporative concentration assists imine formation"}, "mechanism": "4-Aminobutanal undergoes spontaneous intramolecular condensation to the cyclic imine 1-pyrroline.", "reasoning": "The report specifically describes the Strecker-like proline mechanism as proceeding through 4-aminobutanal and 1-pyrroline. This ring closure is chemically plausible under the stated pH range but entropically challenging in dilute solution, so concentration on mineral-rich surfaces is used to make the known route geochemically coherent. Supported by the Strecker-like pathway summarized in the report; this step is literature-supported though upstream production of 4-aminobutanal remains an open systems question."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "HCN addition to 1-pyrroline yielding pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Mineral-assisted cyanation", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Neutral to mildly alkaline pH 7-9 in aqueous solution"}, "mechanism": "Cyanide addition to the cyclic imine forms the corresponding cyclic alpha-aminonitrile, pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile.", "reasoning": "This is the key Strecker-like cyanation step explicitly described in the literature summary: 1-pyrroline plus HCN gives pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile. Supported by classical Strecker logic and the specific proline-focused pathway discussed in the report. The cyclic aminonitrile produced converges with the cyanosulfidic route, matching the requested network convergence."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Hydrothermal synthesis of pyruvate from CO2 and H2", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Magnetite/greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline vent conditions with redox gradients and Fe-S mineral surfaces"}, "mechanism": "Sequential CO2 reduction and C-C bond-forming protometabolic chemistry on Fe-S/oxide mineral surfaces generates the alpha-keto acid pyruvate.", "reasoning": "The user instructions specifically require pyruvate synthesis from CO2 and H2 on magnetite/greigite in hydrothermal environments, and the report places pyruvate as a key alpha-keto-acid precursor for the proto-metabolic route to proline. While individual elementary steps remain an active research area, the hydrothermal generation of pyruvate-like rTCA intermediates on Fe-bearing minerals is aligned with metabolism-first scenarios. Supported conceptually by Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2019; Stubbs et al., 2020-2022 as summarized in the report. This is a connective but literature-consistent node."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Hydrothermal synthesis of glyoxylate from CO2 under iron-sulfur catalysis", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mo