& Moran, 2019 and Stubbs et al., 2020-2022."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Transamination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "353K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe minerals in hydrothermal aqueous medium", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Mild vent-like conditions; ammonia as amine donor analogue"}, "mechanism": "The alpha-keto acid accepts nitrogen via abiotic transamination/reductive amination chemistry to give glutamate.", "reasoning": "The report states that alpha-ketoglutarate reacts with an amine donor such as glycine or ammonia to form glutamate, and cites experimental transamination of alpha-ketoglutarate under mild aqueous conditions. The exact catalyst in the cited yield study is alum, but the present network embeds this within the required hydrothermal mineral context while preserving the documented transformation. Supported by Stubbs and Moran, 2020-2022; the report also notes a 44% glutamate yield at 80 degrees C in the presence of AlK(SO4)2, highlighting plausibility though catalyst identity varies."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Partial reduction of glutamate to glutamate-5-semialdehyde and spontaneous cyclization to P5C", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_017"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "313-373K", "pressure": "variable", "catalyst": "Fe2+ or transition-metal-mediated reduction possible", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Concentrated prebiotic pool or mineral interface; spontaneous intramolecular cyclization after partial reduction"}, "mechanism": "Glutamate undergoes partial reduction to the semialdehyde, which rapidly cyclizes intramolecularly to Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate.", "reasoning": "The report explicitly gives this as the hydrothermal/biochemical logic congruent with modern biology: glutamate is partially reduced to glutamate-5-semialdehyde, which spontaneously cyclizes to P5C. The reduction is proposed to be driven by H2 or transition-metal ions such as Fe2+. Supported by the report's synthesis of modern biochemical analogy and hydrothermal plausibility; this remains a mechanistically plausible but less directly benchmarked abiotic step than pyruvate/glyoxylate coupling."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Reduction of P5C to proline", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "313-373K", "pressure": "variable", "catalyst": "Fe2+ or other transition metal reductants", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Anoxic reducing conditions; hydrothermal or mineral-interface maturation"}, "mechanism": "The cyclic imine/carboxylate P5C is reduced at the imine center to afford proline.", "reasoning": "The report explicitly identifies reduction of P5C by H2 or transition metal ions such as Fe2+ as the terminal step of the proto-metabolic route to proline. This route aligns with modern proline biosynthesis and is therefore highly relevant for continuity from geochemistry to biochemistry. Supported by Stubbs and Moran, 2020-2022 as contextual support for abiotic protometabolism, and by the biochemical analogy discussed in the provided review."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Hydration of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile to prolinamide", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "353K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Aqueous thermal maturation", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Evaporitic or geothermal maturation conditions"}, "mechanism": "Partial hydrolysis of the nitrile converts it to the corresponding amide, prolinamide.", "reasoning": "The report specifically identifies prolinamide as a stable prebiotic intermediate detected in simulated synthesis and a precursor to proline-containing cyclic dipeptides. Including it as a l