yoxylate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)/p-1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H6O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "alpha-ketoglutarate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C5H9NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "glutamic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H7NO2", "iupac_name": "5-oxopyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C5H10N2O", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carboxamide", "common_name": "prolinamide", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C10H16N2O2", "iupac_name": "3,6-di(pyrrolidin-2-yl)piperazine-2,5-dione", "common_name": "cyclo(Pro-Pro)", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Cyanosulfidic Cu-photoredox coupling of HCN and acetylene to acrylonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox system on illuminated mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation; neutral to mildly buffered aqueous conditions; H2S as stoichiometric reductant in cyanosulfidic network"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox chemistry promotes cross-coupling of hydrogen cyanide and acetylene, generating acrylonitrile as the key three-carbon nitrile intermediate.", "reasoning": "This is the core literature-supported entry to proline in cyanosulfidic systems chemistry, where HCN, acetylene, H2S, water, and UV light generate acrylonitrile by Cu-photoredox coupling. Surface mineral agents are included to satisfy the required prebiotic surface setting, while the Cu cycle itself follows the reported chemistry. Supported by the deep report summary of Sutherland-group cyanosulfidic chemistry and photoredox nitrile homologation under mild conditions around 35C (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Reductive homologation of acrylonitrile to 2-aminopentanedinitrile", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_001", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photoredox with sulfide-mediated reduction", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Neutral pH; cyanosulfidic reductive homologation sequence; H2S as stoichiometric reductant"}, "mechanism": "Acrylonitrile undergoes cyanide addition and photoreductive homologation to furnish a five-carbon dinitrile bearing an amino substituent.", "reasoning": "The deep research identifies reductive homologation of acrylonitrile in the presence of H2S and UV as leading to 2-aminopentanedinitrile, the direct precursor to ring closure. This step is central to the Sutherland-style systems chemistry route and is retained without inventing alternative chemistry. Supported by cyanosulfidic amino-acid precursor chemistry under UV/H2S conditions (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Cyclization of 2-aminopentanedinitrile to pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borate minerals (colemanite, ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Mineral-assisted concentration and ring closure", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Evaporative concentration or wet-dry concentration enhances intramolecular cyclization"}, "mechanism": "Intramolecular attack of the amino group onto a nitrile-derived electrophilic center closes the five-membered pyrrolidine framework, leaving one nitrile as the alpha-aminonitrile functionality.", "reasoning": "The report identifies cyclization of the five-carbon dinitrile as the decisive ring-closure step en route to pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile and flags ring closure as a major bottleneck in dilute solution. Mineral-assisted concentration on clays and evaporative settings are therefore used explicitly to address the entropic barrier while staying within the reported geochemical framework. This step is literature-guided but geochemical implementation on minerals is partly connective and thus moderately speculative. Supported by the proline cyanosulfidic pathway summarized in the report and by mineral concentration logic for prebiotic ring closure (Patel et al., 2015; Ferris, 2005; Cleaves et al., 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Hydrolysis of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile to proline", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "353-373K", "pressure": "variable", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "Warm aqueous hydrolysis; kinetic bottleneck; geochemical sweet spot required to balance hydrolysis against decomposition"}, "mechanism": "Progressive hydration of the nitrile gives the corresponding amide and then carboxylic acid, yielding proline.", "reasoning": "The literature explicitly identifies pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile as the immediate alpha-aminonitrile precursor and its hydrolysis to proline as the terminal step, but also emphasizes that nitrile hydrolysis is a key bottleneck requiring elevated temperature and careful conditions. This reaction therefore uses warm aqueous maturation rather than claiming unrealistically facile conversion. Supported by classic aminonitrile hydrolysis logic and the report\u2019s specific discussion of the bottleneck for proline synthesis (Miller, 1957; Cleaves, 2008; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Strecker-like formation of 4-aminobutanal from smaller carbonyl/nitrogen chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_005", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Mineral concentration and photochemical carbonyl generation", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Neutral to mildly alkaline conditions; this is a connective prebiotic aldehyde-assembly step rather than a directly isolated proline-forming transformation"}, "mechanism": "Surface concentration and multistep aldehyde/ammonia/cyanide chemistry furnish the functionalized four-carbon amino aldehyde required for cyclic imine formation.", "reasoning": "The report states that the Strecker-like route to proline requires a functionalized four-carbon aldehyde such as 4-aminobutanal and that such aldehydes could arise from condensation of smaller aldehydes or reductive homologation of HCN. Because the upstream chemistry is not specified in the report as a single definitive reaction, this node is included as a necessary connective step and is explicitly marked as partially speculative but literature-consistent. Supported conceptually by Strecker chemistry and the report\u2019s specific mention of 4-aminobutanal as a precursor (Strecker, 1850; Cleaves, 2008; the review summary in the provided report)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Intramolecular cyclization of 4-aminobutanal to 1-pyrroline", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borate minerals (colemanite, ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Mineral-assisted concentration", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Neutral to mildly alkaline pH; evaporation/concentration helps overcome entropic penalty for ring closure"}, "mechanism": "The amino aldehyde undergoes intramolecular condensation to the five-membered cyclic imine 1-pyrroline.", "reasoning": "The report explicitly identifies intramolecular condensation of 4-aminobutanal to 1-pyrroline as the key cyclic-imine step in the Strecker-like route and highlights ring closure as a major challenge in dilute solution. Clay- and evaporite-assisted concentration are used here to address that documented bottleneck. Supported by the Strecker-like proline route summarized in the report and by general prebiotic concentration chemistry on clays (Cleaves, 2008; Ferris, 2005)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Cyanation of 1-pyrroline to pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Mineral-surface cyanide addition", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 7-9 as consistent with aqueous Strecker-type chemistry"}, "mechanism": "HCN adds to the cyclic imine to generate the corresponding alpha-aminonitrile, pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile.", "reasoning": "This step is directly described in the report as the Strecker-like cyanation of the cyclic imine 1-pyrroline to pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile. The pH window follows the report\u2019s statement that Strecker chemistry is feasible under neutral to mildly alkaline aqueous conditions. Supported by classical Strecker aminonitrile formation and the provided review\u2019s proline-specific cyclic-imine pathway (Strecker, 1850; Cleaves, 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Hydrothermal synthesis of pyruvate from CO2/H2 protometabolism", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Greigite and magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent setting; H2-rich, anoxic, pH-gradient environment; dissolved CO2 and H2 implicitly supplied by vent chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Iron-sulfur and iron-oxide minerals mediate stepwise CO2 reduction and carbon-carbon bond formation to alpha-keto-acid products including pyruvate.", "reasoning": "The user instructions require hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis on magnetite/greigite at 350-400K, and the review identifies pyruvate as a key alpha-keto-acid input to proto-metabolic proline synthesis. This reaction therefore serves as the hydrothermal feeder to the alpha-ketoglutarate branch. The exact prebiotic route to pyruvate remains less directly constrained than the downstream chemistry, so this step should be viewed as literature-consistent network completion rather than a uniquely established transformation. Supported by hydrothermal CO2 fixation and vent mineral catalysis literature, with downstream relevance from Stubbs and Moran proto-metabolic work (Cody et al., 2000; Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997; Stubbs et al., 2020; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Hydrothermal generation of glyoxylate in iron-sulfur protometabolism", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "FeS/FeS2 mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Anoxic hydrothermal fluid-rock interaction; CO2/H2-derived carbonyl chemistry feeding glyoxylate pool"}, "mechanism": "Iron-sulfur-catalyzed reductive carbon fixation and carbonyl chemistry generate small alpha-keto/oxoacids including glyoxylate.", "reasoning": "The deep report highlights glyoxylate together with pyr