ssolved metal ions", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Ammonia-rich anoxic solution; this is a simplified representation of prebiotic amination/transamination chemistry derived from alpha-keto-acid amination studies"}, "mechanism": "Alpha-ketoglutarate undergoes abiotic amination/transamination to glutamate under warm aqueous mineral-assisted conditions.", "reasoning": "The review identifies alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate as the next step in the hydrothermal proto-metabolic route and cites transamination chemistry as plausible under mild aqueous conditions. Because direct alpha-ketoglutarate plus ammonia to glutamate is less specifically demonstrated than the upstream rTCA-like step, this reaction should be read as a condensed representation of mineral-assisted amination/transamination rather than a fully resolved elementary mechanism. The report specifically notes 44% glutamate formation from alpha-ketoglutarate with glycine at 80C in the presence of AlK(SO4)2, which supports glutamate accessibility even if the exact donor differs. Supported by the report\u2019s cited transamination yield summary and proto-metabolic amino-acid synthesis studies (Stubbs and Moran, 2022; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Cyclization of glutamate-derived semialdehyde to Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "313-353K", "pressure": "variable", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "Represents partial reduction of glutamate to glutamate-5-semialdehyde followed by spontaneous cyclization; transition-metal ions and H2-rich conditions may assist prior reduction"}, "mechanism": "Glutamate is first partially reduced to glutamate-5-semialdehyde, which spontaneously cyclizes to the cyclic imine/carboxylate Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate.", "reasoning": "The report specifically identifies glutamate-5-semialdehyde and P5C as the hydrothermal/biochemical branch leading to proline, but also implies that this is one of the more weakly constrained transitions in abiotic chemistry. This reaction is therefore represented as a maturation step with explicit acknowledgment that the partial selective reduction is an open question, while retaining the exact intermediate mandated by the literature. Supported conceptually by universal biological proline biosynthesis and the prebiotic continuity argument in the review; included as a necessary but less experimentally resolved connection (Stubbs and Moran, 2022; the provided review)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Reduction of Delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate to proline", "inputs": ["mol_016"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "313-353K", "pressure": "variable", "catalyst": "Fe2+ or H2-assisted reduction", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Anoxic reducing conditions; hydrothermal-to-pool transfer compatible"}, "mechanism": "Reduction of the cyclic imine in P5C yields proline.", "reasoning": "The report explicitly states that reduction of P5C by H2 or transition metal ions such as Fe2+ yields proline. This is the most direct hydrothermal/biochemical terminal step and is retained exactly from the literature narrative. As with other abiotic routes, the immediate product is expected to be racemic unless later chiral enrichment occurs. Supported by the hydrothermal proto-metabolic route summarized in the review (Stubbs and Moran, 2022; the provided review)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Partial hydrolysis of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile to prolinamide", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "333-353K", "pressure": "variable", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "Controlled partial nitrile hydration in concentrated pools"}, "mechanism": "Nitrile hydration stops at the amide stage, giving prolinamide as a stable maturation intermediate.", "reasoning": "The report highlights prolinamide as a stable prebiotic precursor and specifically relevant to downstream cyclic dipeptide formation under wet-dry conditions. This reaction therefore captures the alternative hydrolysis branch from the common aminonitrile hub without inventing unrelated intermediates. Supported by the review\u2019s discussion of prolinamide in simulated prebiotic chemistry and peptide maturation scenarios (the provided review; Danger et al., 2012 for peptide/amide relevance)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Hydrolysis of prolinamide to proline", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "353-373K", "pressure": "variable", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "Warm aqueous maturation"}, "mechanism": "Amide hydrolysis converts prolinamide into the amino acid proline.", "reasoning": "Given the report\u2019s identification of prolinamide as a stable precursor to proline-containing prebiotic products, amide hydrolysis provides a chemically direct maturation route to proline. This is a reasonable completion step grounded in standard amide hydrolysis chemistry and the role of prolinamide in the supplied review. Supported by the provided review and general prebiotic amide hydrolysis logic (Cleaves, 2008; the provided review)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Wet-dry condensation of prolinamide to cyclo(Pro-Pro)", "inputs": ["mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "353K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "trimetaphosphate-enhanced, pH oscillation 7-11", "aqueous": "false", "other": "Wet-dry cycling; calcite enhances yield approximately 2.23-fold in reported models"}, "mechanism": "Dehydrative condensation and cyclization of prolinamide units yield the diketopiperazine cyclo(Pro-Pro).", "reasoning": "The review specifically reports synthesis of cyclo-Pro-Pro from prolinamide at 80C under pH oscillation 7-11, enhanced by trimetaphosphate and calcite. This reaction is included as a literature-backed maturation branch showing that proline precursors flow into peptide-like products in subaerial cycles. Supported by pH-oscillating prebiotic peptide studies summarized in the report (Rodriguez-Garcia et al., 2015; the provided review)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Hydrolytic back-conversion of cyclo(Pro-Pro) to proline pool", "inputs": ["mol_018", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "333-373K", "pressure": "variable", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "Long-timescale pool/membrane interface hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "Hydrolytic opening and breakdown of the diketopiperazine returns proline to the soluble amino-acid pool.", "reasoning": "This is a connective recovery step allowing the prolinamide/cyclic-dipeptide branch to feed back into the proline node. While not the primary emphasis of the review, it is chemically reasonable and necessary to keep the network fully connected and to represent reversible maturation in prebiotic pools. It should be considered a modestly speculative but justified systems-chemistry link. Supported by general diketopiperazine hydrolysis chemistry and the review\u2019s emphasis on wet-dry peptide cycling (Biron et al., 2006; the provided review)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Core cyanosulfidic nitrile route", "description": "HCN, acetylene, and H2S in UV-driven surface photoredox chemistry give acrylonitrile, then 2-aminopentanedinitrile, then pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, followed by hydrolysis to proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_008"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Cyanosulfidic route with prolinamide maturation", "description": "The same cyanosulfidic aminonitrile hub feeds partial hydrolysis to pro